  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>
  <p>No model is complete. Here's what a DCF inherently misses — and how it might bias our estimate.</p>

  <h3>Upside risks (our number could be too low)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Interest rate cuts:</strong> REITs are highly sensitive to rates. If the Fed cuts rates aggressively, Welltower's cost of capital falls, and intrinsic value increases (see sensitivity table).</li>
    <li><strong>Faster development pipeline:</strong> If their development pipeline stabilizes quicker than expected, FCF could jump past our 15% projection.</li>
    <li><strong>Demographic acceleration:</strong> The "silver tsunami" of aging boomers may drive occupancy levels to 90%+ much faster than modeled.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks (our number could be too high)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Labor costs:</strong> Senior housing requires massive nursing and staffing labor. Wage inflation could compress margins significantly.</li>
    <li><strong>Higher for longer rates:</strong> Since Welltower relies on debt to acquire properties, sustained high interest rates make growth more expensive and lower net FCF.</li>
    <li><strong>New supply:</strong> While supply is currently constrained, a boom in senior housing construction could dampen rent growth pricing power.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use DCF instead of FFO or AFFO multiples?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">While FFO (Funds From Operations) and AFFO are standard real estate metrics, multiples just tell you relative pricing. A DCF forces explicit assumptions about real cash generation, growth, and the cost of debt/equity, providing an absolute value rather than a relative one.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why 9% discount rate and not higher?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">The discount rate represents the required return. The 10-year Treasury yields 4.18%. For a healthcare REIT with highly predictable demographic tailwinds and tangible real estate assets, the equity risk premium is lower than a volatile tech stock. 9% is a standard hurdle rate for premium real estate operators.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why 15% FCF growth for a real estate company?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">15% is high for standard real estate, but Welltower is in a unique post-COVID recovery phase combined with a demographic inflection point. Supply of new senior housing is at historic lows, while demand is surging, giving them massive pricing power and rapid NOI growth.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is this a buy recommendation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">No. This is an analytical framework for estimating intrinsic value. Whether to buy depends on your personal risk tolerance, portfolio allocation, time horizon, tax situation, and conviction in the assumptions. We provide the tools and transparency — you make the decision.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

